All right.

00:26:41.430 --> 00:26:45.430
So the Bohr model, we've
now rolled it all out.

00:26:45.430 --> 00:26:46.890
We have the energy portrait.

00:26:46.890 --> 00:26:49.230
We have the radii, discrete.

00:26:49.230 --> 00:26:50.750
We have quantization.

00:26:50.750 --> 00:26:52.660
And we have velocities
if we ever want to

00:26:52.660 --> 00:26:53.550
look at those again.

00:26:53.550 --> 00:26:56.120
Now what's the next thing
we do in science?

00:26:56.120 --> 00:27:00.110
We compare the predictions of
the Bohr model with data.

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:01.640
Are there any data
to support this?

00:27:01.640 --> 00:27:04.370
Because remember, all Rutherford
said was plum

00:27:04.370 --> 00:27:05.690
pudding doesn't make sense.

00:27:05.690 --> 00:27:08.070
Instead I'm going to concentrate
the positive mass

00:27:08.070 --> 00:27:08.950
in the center.

00:27:08.950 --> 00:27:12.030
And then Bohr came along and
said, not only is it going to

00:27:12.030 --> 00:27:15.350
be a planetary model, I'm going
to have circular orbits.

00:27:15.350 --> 00:27:17.600
So now we've gone a long way
from Geiger-Marsden.

00:27:17.600 --> 00:27:19.700
So is there any data?

00:27:19.700 --> 00:27:23.620
Well there were data in 1853.

00:27:23.620 --> 00:27:26.500
Remember, Bohr published
this in 1913.

00:27:26.500 --> 00:27:30.820
In 1853 there was a
spectroscopist by the name--

00:27:30.820 --> 00:27:32.570
I'm going to tell
you his name--

00:27:32.570 --> 00:27:36.360
in Uppsala, Sweden.

00:27:36.360 --> 00:27:38.570
And his name was Angstrom.

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:45.710
Angstrom was doing experiments
on hydrogen in

00:27:45.710 --> 00:27:48.140
gas discharge tubes.

00:27:48.140 --> 00:27:58.680
So he measured emissions from
gas discharge tube.

00:28:01.200 --> 00:28:04.810
And it was filled with
various gases

00:28:04.810 --> 00:28:08.890
including atomic hydrogen.

00:28:08.890 --> 00:28:12.550
And in order to take his
data, what he used

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:15.050
was this device here--

00:28:15.050 --> 00:28:17.330
there's the Bohr radius,
just an example.

00:28:17.330 --> 00:28:19.740
He used the prism
spectrograph.

00:28:19.740 --> 00:28:21.230
So here's a gas discharge
tube.

00:28:21.230 --> 00:28:23.300
And I'm going to show you the
physics of that in a second.

00:28:23.300 --> 00:28:24.890
Basically you've got a
pair of electrodes.

00:28:24.890 --> 00:28:26.135
You've got gas in the tube.

00:28:26.135 --> 00:28:30.080
And as this cartoon shows, you
apply a potential across the

00:28:30.080 --> 00:28:30.750
electrodes.

00:28:30.750 --> 00:28:33.170
And beyond a certain threshold
potential, the

00:28:33.170 --> 00:28:34.860
tube begins to glow.

00:28:34.860 --> 00:28:36.530
And the glow goes in
all directions.

00:28:36.530 --> 00:28:38.110
And a blinds you when
you're in the lab.

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:40.410
So what you do, is you
cover this up a bit.

00:28:40.410 --> 00:28:41.760
You have a narrow slit.

00:28:41.760 --> 00:28:44.260
And then you force the light
to come through in a thin

00:28:44.260 --> 00:28:46.880
ribbon, and then expose
it to a prism.

00:28:46.880 --> 00:28:50.850
What the prism does, is it takes
the light and breaks it

00:28:50.850 --> 00:28:54.490
into its components, sort of
rainbow-like, and magnifies

00:28:54.490 --> 00:28:56.630
the difference.

00:28:56.630 --> 00:28:59.560
As refraction goes, different
wavelengths will refract

00:28:59.560 --> 00:29:00.550
different amounts.

00:29:00.550 --> 00:29:02.420
And then you shoot this
across the room.

00:29:05.280 --> 00:29:06.430
There's two counters.

00:29:06.430 --> 00:29:09.340
One is a scintillation screen
and an army of graduate

00:29:09.340 --> 00:29:10.980
students who sit there
in the dark.

00:29:10.980 --> 00:29:13.690
But they're no good because you
can't stick them into the

00:29:13.690 --> 00:29:14.570
publication.

00:29:14.570 --> 00:29:17.120
You need to have data that
people will rely upon.

00:29:17.120 --> 00:29:19.460
So instead you use a
photographic plate.

00:29:19.460 --> 00:29:23.740
And if you put even a tiny,
tiny angle of separation

00:29:23.740 --> 00:29:26.380
across a great enough distance,
you start to get

00:29:26.380 --> 00:29:28.090
enough line splitting
that you can see.

00:29:28.090 --> 00:29:29.030
And then you go backwards.

00:29:29.030 --> 00:29:30.230
And you know the
geometry here.

00:29:30.230 --> 00:29:32.870
And you can figure out what the
wavelength must have been

00:29:32.870 --> 00:29:34.710
to go this distance, et
cetera, et cetera.

00:29:34.710 --> 00:29:38.070
And these are all color coded,
not because they had color

00:29:38.070 --> 00:29:41.400
film in those days, but just
to let you know that 656

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:45.150
nanometers, if you were the
graduate student sitting

00:29:45.150 --> 00:29:47.470
there, you'd see a red line, a
green line, a blue line, and a

00:29:47.470 --> 00:29:49.330
violent line.

00:29:49.330 --> 00:29:50.580
So that's how he made
the measurements.

00:29:54.070 --> 00:29:56.140
And he published those
measurements.

00:29:56.140 --> 00:30:00.510
And so they lay.

00:30:00.510 --> 00:30:03.620
And then the story gets
a little thicker.

00:30:03.620 --> 00:30:09.310
In 1885, there's a Swiss high
school math teacher.

00:30:09.310 --> 00:30:10.720
I mean, I can't make
this stuff.

00:30:10.720 --> 00:30:12.030
This is true story.

00:30:12.030 --> 00:30:15.040
There's a Swiss high school math
teacher by the name of J.

00:30:15.040 --> 00:30:15.310
J.

00:30:15.310 --> 00:30:16.290
Balmer.

00:30:16.290 --> 00:30:16.720
We had J.

00:30:16.720 --> 00:30:16.940
J.

00:30:16.940 --> 00:30:17.440
Thomson.

00:30:17.440 --> 00:30:18.070
Now we've got J.

00:30:18.070 --> 00:30:18.280
J.

00:30:18.280 --> 00:30:19.300
Balmer.

00:30:19.300 --> 00:30:19.630
And J.

00:30:19.630 --> 00:30:19.770
J.

00:30:19.770 --> 00:30:22.620
Balmer, he loved to
play with numbers.

00:30:22.620 --> 00:30:25.640
And he was studying
this set of lines.

00:30:25.640 --> 00:30:27.730
And he was trying to come
up with a pattern.

00:30:27.730 --> 00:30:28.840
Can you see a pattern there?

00:30:28.840 --> 00:30:33.160
410 434 486, 656, do
they go squares?

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:35.180
Are they primes?

00:30:35.180 --> 00:30:36.380
What's the pattern there?

00:30:36.380 --> 00:30:39.440
So Balmer puzzled over
this for awhile.

00:30:39.440 --> 00:30:42.480
And he finally came up with
the equation to represent

00:30:42.480 --> 00:30:43.650
those lines.

00:30:43.650 --> 00:30:49.640
So he studied Angstrom's
data found the pattern.

00:30:53.150 --> 00:30:54.870
And here's the pattern
that he found.

00:30:54.870 --> 00:30:58.450
He said that those
are wavelengths.

00:30:58.450 --> 00:31:04.720
If I take instead wave number,
nu bar is called wave number,

00:31:04.720 --> 00:31:09.660
which is the reciprocal
of the wavelength.

00:31:09.660 --> 00:31:13.430
So if I take the reciprocal of
the wavelength, I end up with

00:31:13.430 --> 00:31:17.980
those 4 lines conforming to a
series that goes like this.

00:31:17.980 --> 00:31:22.780
1 over 2 squared minus 1
over n squared, where n

00:31:22.780 --> 00:31:27.260
equals 3, 4, 5, 6.

00:31:27.260 --> 00:31:30.510
And there's a constant here
which we're going

00:31:30.510 --> 00:31:32.330
to designate r.

00:31:32.330 --> 00:31:34.790
And the value of R--

00:31:34.790 --> 00:31:37.480
I'm going to put that
on the next board--

00:31:37.480 --> 00:31:43.040
the value of R as expressed in
SI units today, would be 1.1

00:31:43.040 --> 00:31:46.740
times 10 to the 7 reciprocal
meters.

00:31:46.740 --> 00:31:48.390
Wavelength is a meter.

00:31:48.390 --> 00:31:50.370
Reciprocal wavelength
or wave number must

00:31:50.370 --> 00:31:52.120
be reciprocal meters.

00:31:52.120 --> 00:31:56.160
So how this all of this support
the Bohr model?

00:31:56.160 --> 00:31:58.450
Well in order to explain it,
I've got a first tell you what

00:31:58.450 --> 00:32:01.200
the physics of the gas
discharge tube are.

00:32:01.200 --> 00:32:06.520
So let's go inside the gas
discharge tube and understand

00:32:06.520 --> 00:32:07.200
those physics.

00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:09.410
So here's the gas
discharge tube.

00:32:09.410 --> 00:32:12.830
It's made are borosilicate
glass.

00:32:12.830 --> 00:32:15.390
And we fill it with gas.

00:32:15.390 --> 00:32:19.530
And in this case, the gas is
going to contain among other

00:32:19.530 --> 00:32:21.660
things hydrogen.

00:32:21.660 --> 00:32:25.120
So this is a hydrogen
gas phase atom.

00:32:25.120 --> 00:32:27.340
And this is probably
at low pressure.

00:32:27.340 --> 00:32:29.330
And then I said I
need electrode.

00:32:29.330 --> 00:32:31.200
I'll get the electrodes
inside.

00:32:31.200 --> 00:32:33.320
So I've got to have a really
good glass blower who can make

00:32:33.320 --> 00:32:35.330
a glass to metal seal,
and have a

00:32:35.330 --> 00:32:37.670
feedthrough to an electrode.

00:32:37.670 --> 00:32:39.800
So this is still
a vacuum seal.

00:32:39.800 --> 00:32:41.420
How do they get the gas
in the first place?

00:32:41.420 --> 00:32:42.550
We don't show you this
in the books.

00:32:42.550 --> 00:32:44.430
I'll tell you because I
did this in my Ph.D.

00:32:44.430 --> 00:32:47.430
What you do is you have a
little side tube here.

00:32:47.430 --> 00:32:49.380
You evacuate.

00:32:49.380 --> 00:32:52.300
This goes to a vacuum pump.

00:32:52.300 --> 00:32:54.190
And then over here you
have a gas source.

00:32:54.190 --> 00:32:55.440
You evacuate.

00:32:55.440 --> 00:32:57.520
Put in the gas to whatever
pressure you want.

00:32:57.520 --> 00:33:00.230
And then the glass blower
disconnects.

00:33:00.230 --> 00:33:02.170
This pulls this down
to a reduced

00:33:02.170 --> 00:33:05.200
pressure, and seals it.

00:33:05.200 --> 00:33:06.880
But the books don't
show you that.

00:33:06.880 --> 00:33:09.650
That's a secret.

00:33:09.650 --> 00:33:11.310
So we've got a gas
at low pressure.

00:33:11.310 --> 00:33:13.320
And I've got an electrode
over here and an

00:33:13.320 --> 00:33:14.270
electrode over here.

00:33:14.270 --> 00:33:18.055
And they're connected to a
variable voltage power supply.

00:33:18.055 --> 00:33:20.200
So I'm going to put an arrow
with the V meaning it's

00:33:20.200 --> 00:33:21.070
variable voltage.

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:22.650
I can change the voltage.

00:33:22.650 --> 00:33:24.730
And this convention, this
is the negative side.

00:33:24.730 --> 00:33:26.680
So this means the electrons
leave the power

00:33:26.680 --> 00:33:27.950
supply and go like this.

00:33:27.950 --> 00:33:30.300
Which means this electrode
will be negative.

00:33:30.300 --> 00:33:32.530
And this electrode
will be positive.

00:33:32.530 --> 00:33:35.390
And thanks to Michael Faraday,
we will call

00:33:35.390 --> 00:33:37.270
this one the cathode.

00:33:37.270 --> 00:33:39.100
And this one we will
call the anode.

00:33:41.880 --> 00:33:43.080
Now what happens?

00:33:43.080 --> 00:33:45.660
We start turning up the
pressure, turning up the

00:33:45.660 --> 00:33:46.650
voltage rather.

00:33:46.650 --> 00:33:47.820
Low pressure here, but

00:33:47.820 --> 00:33:49.890
electrical pressure is voltage.

00:33:49.890 --> 00:33:53.760
The voltage gets high enough,
eventually the electrons will

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:56.170
boil off the cathode.

00:33:56.170 --> 00:33:58.030
And this is a gas
at low pressure.

00:33:58.030 --> 00:34:00.690
And they will accelerate from
rest and go all the way across

00:34:00.690 --> 00:34:03.120
the tube and crash
into the anode.

00:34:03.120 --> 00:34:05.130
And we complete the circuit.

00:34:05.130 --> 00:34:07.770
But if there's a gas in here,
some of these electrons are

00:34:07.770 --> 00:34:10.000
going to hit the
gas molecules.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:12.330
And when they hit the gas
molecules, if they have enough

00:34:12.330 --> 00:34:17.760
energy to do so, they will cause
electrons inside the gas

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:19.730
molecules to be excited.

00:34:23.170 --> 00:34:26.740
And if they're excited enough,
the electrons will jump up to

00:34:26.740 --> 00:34:28.100
a higher energy level.

00:34:28.100 --> 00:34:30.180
But they can't be sustained.

00:34:30.180 --> 00:34:32.410
Because this is a ballistic
collision.

00:34:32.410 --> 00:34:33.220
It's a one of.

00:34:33.220 --> 00:34:34.520
It's like a bowling alley.

00:34:34.520 --> 00:34:37.910
One ball, one pin, one impact.

00:34:37.910 --> 00:34:39.030
Now the pin is in the air.

00:34:39.030 --> 00:34:40.490
What happens to the pin?

00:34:40.490 --> 00:34:41.540
It falls back down.

00:34:41.540 --> 00:34:41.870
Why?

00:34:41.870 --> 00:34:43.690
Because gravity pulls it down.

00:34:43.690 --> 00:34:47.030
In this case, you've got the
energetics pulling the

00:34:47.030 --> 00:34:48.170
electron back down.

00:34:48.170 --> 00:34:50.760
Now the electron goes from high
energy to low energy.

00:34:50.760 --> 00:34:54.380
And when that happens, the
energy difference is given off

00:34:54.380 --> 00:34:57.200
in the form of a photon.

00:34:57.200 --> 00:35:01.690
So I get photon emission when
this falls back down.

00:35:01.690 --> 00:35:05.730
And this photon has
a wavelength.

00:35:05.730 --> 00:35:09.820
What I'm going to show you is
that the set of lines that you

00:35:09.820 --> 00:35:14.860
get from exactly this
configuration using this

00:35:14.860 --> 00:35:19.100
equation give you the
Balmer series.

00:35:19.100 --> 00:35:23.710
So now you've got a model that
Bohr postulated for atomic

00:35:23.710 --> 00:35:28.460
hydrogen on 1-electron atom that
exactly predicts that set

00:35:28.460 --> 00:35:29.680
of 4 lines.

00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:33.670
Which were measured
50 years before.

00:35:33.670 --> 00:35:35.160
So let's go.

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:38.520
So first of all let's
get the energy here.

00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:40.220
And I'm going to get the energy
of this electron.

00:35:40.220 --> 00:35:44.110
This electron I'm going to call
a ballistic electron.

00:35:44.110 --> 00:35:46.080
Why do I call it a ballistic
electron?

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:47.580
Because it's not bound.

00:35:47.580 --> 00:35:48.240
It's free.

00:35:48.240 --> 00:35:51.790
It boils off the cathode, flies
through free space, and

00:35:51.790 --> 00:35:52.850
crashes into an anode.

00:35:52.850 --> 00:35:55.050
Clearly it's not part
of an atom.

00:35:55.050 --> 00:35:57.270
But there's a second electron
in this story.

00:35:57.270 --> 00:35:59.950
And it's the ground state
electron in hydrogen.

00:35:59.950 --> 00:36:01.200
And it lives here.

00:36:04.080 --> 00:36:06.070
So what's the energy of the
ballistic electron?

00:36:10.490 --> 00:36:14.750
Well that's just 1/2 mv squared
And where did it get

00:36:14.750 --> 00:36:15.640
its energy from?

00:36:15.640 --> 00:36:18.070
It got its energy from
the power supply.

00:36:18.070 --> 00:36:20.330
And what's the electrostatic
energy?

00:36:20.330 --> 00:36:24.200
It's the product of the charge
on the species times the

00:36:24.200 --> 00:36:27.270
voltage through which
it was accelerated.

00:36:27.270 --> 00:36:29.710
So away we go.

00:36:29.710 --> 00:36:32.190
I know the charge on the
electron is minus E.

00:36:32.190 --> 00:36:34.300
Whatever the voltage is
there, 1 volt, 10

00:36:34.300 --> 00:36:35.960
volts, 100 volts, whatever.

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:37.560
Away we go.

00:36:37.560 --> 00:36:40.630
By the way, I'm going to show
you just one other thing in

00:36:40.630 --> 00:36:42.580
terms of order of magnitude.

00:36:42.580 --> 00:36:46.290
The kinds of voltages you see
along here are 1 volt, 10

00:36:46.290 --> 00:36:47.650
volts, that sort of thing.

00:36:47.650 --> 00:36:57.160
So suppose, to get an order of
magnitude, suppose we had a

00:36:57.160 --> 00:37:02.070
species of charge E.

00:37:02.070 --> 00:37:05.255
So in other words, it's only 1
times the elementary charge.

00:37:05.255 --> 00:37:14.370
A species of charge
E influenced by

00:37:14.370 --> 00:37:18.350
voltage of 1 volt.

00:37:18.350 --> 00:37:23.040
So this is 1 in the voltage
units, and 1 in the elementary

00:37:23.040 --> 00:37:24.000
charge units.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:25.310
How much energy would that be?

00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:28.260
That's equivalent to making
1 volt and accelerate an

00:37:28.260 --> 00:37:33.110
electron from rest
across this gap.

00:37:33.110 --> 00:37:37.400
And the result would be, the
energy then would simply equal

00:37:37.400 --> 00:37:46.260
1.6 times 10 to the minus 19
coulombs times 1 volt.

00:37:46.260 --> 00:37:47.720
And what's the energy
going to be?

00:37:47.720 --> 00:37:49.330
Well I've got coulombs
times volts.

00:37:49.330 --> 00:37:51.550
And I don't know how I convert
one to the other.

00:37:51.550 --> 00:37:52.200
I don't have to.

00:37:52.200 --> 00:37:53.170
Why not?

00:37:53.170 --> 00:37:54.570
Because that's an SI unit.

00:37:54.570 --> 00:37:56.040
And that's an SI unit.

00:37:56.040 --> 00:37:57.110
This is an energy.

00:37:57.110 --> 00:37:59.576
So with impunity, I write
1.6 times 10 to

00:37:59.576 --> 00:38:01.400
the minus 19 joules.

00:38:01.400 --> 00:38:04.820
That's the beauty of SI units.

00:38:04.820 --> 00:38:05.820
So that's a good news.

00:38:05.820 --> 00:38:06.560
I know it's joules.

00:38:06.560 --> 00:38:08.640
The bad news is I hate
this number.

00:38:08.640 --> 00:38:10.850
It's a stupid number, 1.6 times
10 to the minus 19.

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:11.450
it's crazy.

00:38:11.450 --> 00:38:14.920
Why don't I come up with
a number like 3, 7?

00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:17.440
So what I could do,
is I could define.

00:38:17.440 --> 00:38:21.070
I could define a unit such
that when the elementary

00:38:21.070 --> 00:38:26.300
charge is accelerated across the
unit voltage, I would call

00:38:26.300 --> 00:38:30.470
that unit 1 electron volt.

00:38:30.470 --> 00:38:32.650
And so somebody thought
of this before me.

00:38:32.650 --> 00:38:35.190
And hence, this is the unit
of the electron volt.

00:38:35.190 --> 00:38:38.790
It takes these crazy things that
we've been spewing here

00:38:38.790 --> 00:38:42.510
up until now, and rationalizes
them into numbers that people

00:38:42.510 --> 00:38:44.060
can carry around
in their heads.

00:38:44.060 --> 00:38:45.380
So what's K now?

00:38:45.380 --> 00:38:48.990
K is 2.18 times 10 to
the minus 18 joules.

00:38:48.990 --> 00:38:49.960
Yuck!

00:38:49.960 --> 00:38:51.700
Let's convert that to
electron volts.

00:38:51.700 --> 00:38:55.100
So I divide by 1.6 times
10 to the minus 19.

00:38:55.100 --> 00:38:58.600
And I got 13.6 electron volts.

00:38:58.600 --> 00:39:02.090
You'll remember that on your
death bed, ionization energy

00:39:02.090 --> 00:39:04.440
of atomic hydrogen.

00:39:04.440 --> 00:39:06.980
Maybe we don't have to give
